y dynasties persist in democracies, and why their numbers are only now beginning to wane in Japan-questions that have long perplexed regional experts. Smith introduces a compelling comparative theory to explain variation in the presence of dynasties across democracies and political parties. Drawing on extensive legislator-level data from twelve democracies and detailed candidate-level data from Japan, he examines the inherited advantage that members of dynasties reap throughout their political careers-from candidate selection, to election, to promotion into cabinet. Smith shows how the nature and extent of this advantage, as well as its consequences for representation, vary significantly with the institutional context of electoral rules and features of party organization. His findings extend far beyond Japan, shedding light on the causes and consequences of dynastic politics for democracies around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDemocracyzJapan. 0aFamiliesxPolitical aspectszJapan. 0aIncumbency (Public officers)zJapan. 0aPolitical partieszJapan. 0aPoliticiansxFamily relationshipszJapan. 4aJapan. 4aLiberal Democratic Party. 4acandidate selection. 4ademocratic dynasties. 4aelectoral system. 4aincumbency advantage. 4ainherited incumbency advantage. 4aparties. 4apolitical institutions. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503606401zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606401.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles